{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01M6BSPmxYcGMDazSVUoJVU6","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I now have full context. Here is the review.\n\n---\n\n# Code Review: Multi-word garbled camelCase detection in `isLikelyGarbled`\n\n## Review Metrics\n\n- Files Reviewed: 1 (`lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`)\n- Critical Issues: 0\n- High Priority: 1\n- Medium Priority: 2\n- Suggestions: 2\n\n## Executive Summary\n\nThe change correctly closes a real gap — the single-word `[a-z][A-Z]` check at line 302 silently passed multi-word garbled inputs. The implementation is mechanically consistent with the existing `hasGarbledWord` pattern directly above it. The main risk is false-positive rejection of legitimate titles containing brand names, acronym-adjacent words, or natural language patterns that happen to contain a lowercase-then-uppercase transition.\n\n---\n\n## HIGH Priority\n\n### Exemption list is too narrow for real recipe OCR\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:342`\n\n**Impact**: Real recipe titles can legitimately trigger `/[a-z][A-Z]/` beyond Scottish/Irish names. Examples:\n\n- Brand names that appear in recipe titles: \"mayoChef dip\", \"canDelight mousse\", or OCR-corrupted runs where a space was dropped between two capitalized words (\"Pasta withGarlic\", \"Beef andPotatoes\")\n- The \"dropped space\" case is particularly dangerous: a clean title where OCR merges two words (\"withGarlic\", \"andPotatoes\") will be rejected as garbled even though the rest of the title is clean. This is a different failure mode from actual garbled tokens like \"XxYyZz\".\n\nThe task document (task-01.md) lists the triggering case as `Xxyyzz salt and pepper` — a token where the transition pattern appears within what is clearly OCR noise. But the regex does not distinguish \"garbled OCR noise token\" from \"two words merged by a dropped space.\"\n\n**Root Cause**: The check conflates two distinct phenomena: (1) intra-word scrambled characters like \"UuIw\" or \"XxYyZz\", and (2) inter-word space drops like \"withGarlic\". The former is always garbled; the latter is an OCR artifact that may exist alongside an otherwise valid title.\n\n**Suggested tightening**: Restrict the match to words that contain the transition at a position that rules out simple merged-word artifacts, or add the minimum word-count guard already used by `looksLikeCookingInstruction` (i.e., only fire this check when the candidate has enough other clean words to be suspicious):\n\n```typescript\n// Only flag if the garbled token is short enough that it cannot plausibly\n// be two merged words (e.g., \"withGarlic\" is 9 chars and might be two words;\n// \"UuIw\" is 4 chars and is not).\nconst hasGarbledCamelCase = words.some(\n  (w) =>\n    w.length >= 3 &&\n    w.length <= 7 &&        // merged-word artifacts are usually longer\n    /[a-z][A-Z]/.test(w) &&\n    !/^(Mc|Mac)[A-Z]/.test(w)\n);\n```\n\nAlternatively, if the intent is specifically to catch short scrambled tokens, the condition could require that the matching word fails a vowel-ratio check (mirroring the top-level check), making it consistent with the rest of the function's approach.\n\n---\n\n## Medium Priority\n\n### Asymmetry with the single-word path is untested\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:302–344`\n\n**Impact**: The single-word check (line 302) and the new multi-word check share the same regex but live in separate branches with no test exercising their boundary. A future refactor that merges or reorders the guards could introduce a regression where a single-word garbled token is tested against the `Mc`/`Mac` exemption (which was not part of the original single-word check). There is no unit test suite for `isLikelyGarbled` itself — all coverage is integration-level via `extractTitle`.\n\n**Root Cause**: `isLikelyGarbled` is a pure function with clear boolean semantics, but it has no direct unit tests. This makes the function harder to reason about as it accumulates guards.\n\n**Suggestion**: Add a `describe(\"isLikelyGarbled\")` block covering at minimum:\n- the new cases from task-01.md: `\"XxYyZz salt and pepper\"` → true, `\"McDonald Spice Blend\"` → false\n- the boundary with the existing single-word path: `\"XxYyZz\"` alone → true (via line 302), `\"Salt and Pepper\"` → false\n\nThis is consistent with the project's testing strategy and the fact that every prior iteration added eval cases to validate changes.\n\n---\n\n### The `Mc`/`Mac` exemption is structurally fragile\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:342`\n\n**Impact**: The exemption `/^(Mc|Mac)[A-Z]/` applies to the whole word `w`, which is correct. However, the comment says \"Exempt Scottish/Irish names\" while the exemption actually covers any word beginning with `Mc` or `Mac` followed by a capital — including OCR noise that happens to start with those characters (unlikely but possible). More practically, similar legitimate name prefixes are not covered: \"O'Brien\" would not trigger the regex at all (apostrophe breaks the transition), but \"DeVito\" or \"LaRosa\" (Italian/French name particles) would fail the check and be flagged as garbled.\n\nThis is low frequency in recipe OCR, but if the exemption list is going to exist, it should either be minimal (what it is now) with a comment acknowledging the gap, or be broadened to cover the general category of name-particle capitalization. The current comment overstates completeness.\n\n**Suggestion**: Update the comment to be honest about scope:\n\n```typescript\n!/^(Mc|Mac)[A-Z]/.test(w) // Narrow exemption: Mc/Mac name prefixes only\n```\n\n---\n\n## Strengths\n\n- The placement inside the existing `if (words.length >= 2)` block is exactly right. It mirrors the structure and naming of `hasGarbledWord` immediately above it, making the code easy to follow.\n- The `w.length >= 3` guard is well-reasoned and documented in task-01.md.\n- The change is minimal and surgical — it does not refactor surrounding logic.\n\n---\n\n## Proactive Suggestions\n\n**Consolidate the two camelCase checks.** The single-word check at line 302 and the new multi-word check are now siblings that test the same pattern. If the `Mc`/`Mac` exemption is valid for multi-word, it is equally valid for single-word (a recipe book for \"McDonald's Classics\" contains a single-word title candidate \"McDonald's\"). Consider whether line 302 should also carry the exemption, and whether the two checks can be unified by removing the `words.length` guard and relying purely on the content test — though the current separate structure is easier to audit, so this is optional.\n\n**Eval case coverage.** The iteration 29 feedback shows the triggering case was `\"Xxyyzz salt and pepper\"` (Pattern 3). The task document lists verification cases but none appear to be wired into the test file. Adding even one integration test case reproducing the Pattern 3 input would prevent this regression from being re-introduced."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: ae7572b5f81b4d134 (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\n<usage>total_tokens: 22969\ntool_uses: 14\nduration_ms: 98432</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8e994769-593d-48a7-bf6b-82b6087d5889","uuid":"e8b74f0b-4d56-4c05-bd52-59dec5c406c6","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Review the following change to `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`. Focus on:\n\n1. Implementation completeness — does the change fully address the task?\n2. Code quality — does it match existing patterns in the file?\n3. Integration — should anything be extracted or refactored?\n4. Codebase consistency — are there places where existing code could benefit from this new check?\n\nThe change adds multi-word garbled camelCase detection inside the `isLikelyGarbled` function. Here's the diff:\n\n```diff\n     if (hasGarbledWord) {\n       return true;\n     }\n+\n+    // Multi-word candidate with a garbled token: a word with internal\n+    // lowercase→uppercase transition that isn't a known camelCase pattern\n+    // (e.g., \"McDonald\", \"McCormick\"). Catches \"XxYyZz\", \"UuIw\" etc.\n+    const hasGarbledCamelCase = words.some(\n+      (w) =>\n+        w.length >= 3 &&\n+        /[a-z][A-Z]/.test(w) &&\n+        !/^(Mc|Mac)[A-Z]/.test(w) // Exempt Scottish/Irish names\n+    );\n+    if (hasGarbledCamelCase) {\n+      return true;\n+    }\n   }\n \n   return false;\n```\n\nContext: the existing single-word check at line 302 is:\n```typescript\nif (words.length === 1 && /[a-z][A-Z]/.test(text.trim())) {\n  return true;\n}\n```\n\nThe new multi-word check is placed inside the `if (words.length >= 2)` block that already handles other multi-word garbled patterns. Please read the full function for context before reviewing.","agentId":"ae7572b5f81b4d134","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I now have full context. Here is the review.\n\n---\n\n# Code Review: Multi-word garbled camelCase detection in `isLikelyGarbled`\n\n## Review Metrics\n\n- Files Reviewed: 1 (`lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`)\n- Critical Issues: 0\n- High Priority: 1\n- Medium Priority: 2\n- Suggestions: 2\n\n## Executive Summary\n\nThe change correctly closes a real gap — the single-word `[a-z][A-Z]` check at line 302 silently passed multi-word garbled inputs. The implementation is mechanically consistent with the existing `hasGarbledWord` pattern directly above it. The main risk is false-positive rejection of legitimate titles containing brand names, acronym-adjacent words, or natural language patterns that happen to contain a lowercase-then-uppercase transition.\n\n---\n\n## HIGH Priority\n\n### Exemption list is too narrow for real recipe OCR\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:342`\n\n**Impact**: Real recipe titles can legitimately trigger `/[a-z][A-Z]/` beyond Scottish/Irish names. Examples:\n\n- Brand names that appear in recipe titles: \"mayoChef dip\", \"canDelight mousse\", or OCR-corrupted runs where a space was dropped between two capitalized words (\"Pasta withGarlic\", \"Beef andPotatoes\")\n- The \"dropped space\" case is particularly dangerous: a clean title where OCR merges two words (\"withGarlic\", \"andPotatoes\") will be rejected as garbled even though the rest of the title is clean. This is a different failure mode from actual garbled tokens like \"XxYyZz\".\n\nThe task document (task-01.md) lists the triggering case as `Xxyyzz salt and pepper` — a token where the transition pattern appears within what is clearly OCR noise. But the regex does not distinguish \"garbled OCR noise token\" from \"two words merged by a dropped space.\"\n\n**Root Cause**: The check conflates two distinct phenomena: (1) intra-word scrambled characters like \"UuIw\" or \"XxYyZz\", and (2) inter-word space drops like \"withGarlic\". The former is always garbled; the latter is an OCR artifact that may exist alongside an otherwise valid title.\n\n**Suggested tightening**: Restrict the match to words that contain the transition at a position that rules out simple merged-word artifacts, or add the minimum word-count guard already used by `looksLikeCookingInstruction` (i.e., only fire this check when the candidate has enough other clean words to be suspicious):\n\n```typescript\n// Only flag if the garbled token is short enough that it cannot plausibly\n// be two merged words (e.g., \"withGarlic\" is 9 chars and might be two words;\n// \"UuIw\" is 4 chars and is not).\nconst hasGarbledCamelCase = words.some(\n  (w) =>\n    w.length >= 3 &&\n    w.length <= 7 &&        // merged-word artifacts are usually longer\n    /[a-z][A-Z]/.test(w) &&\n    !/^(Mc|Mac)[A-Z]/.test(w)\n);\n```\n\nAlternatively, if the intent is specifically to catch short scrambled tokens, the condition could require that the matching word fails a vowel-ratio check (mirroring the top-level check), making it consistent with the rest of the function's approach.\n\n---\n\n## Medium Priority\n\n### Asymmetry with the single-word path is untested\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:302–344`\n\n**Impact**: The single-word check (line 302) and the new multi-word check share the same regex but live in separate branches with no test exercising their boundary. A future refactor that merges or reorders the guards could introduce a regression where a single-word garbled token is tested against the `Mc`/`Mac` exemption (which was not part of the original single-word check). There is no unit test suite for `isLikelyGarbled` itself — all coverage is integration-level via `extractTitle`.\n\n**Root Cause**: `isLikelyGarbled` is a pure function with clear boolean semantics, but it has no direct unit tests. This makes the function harder to reason about as it accumulates guards.\n\n**Suggestion**: Add a `describe(\"isLikelyGarbled\")` block covering at minimum:\n- the new cases from task-01.md: `\"XxYyZz salt and pepper\"` → true, `\"McDonald Spice Blend\"` → false\n- the boundary with the existing single-word path: `\"XxYyZz\"` alone → true (via line 302), `\"Salt and Pepper\"` → false\n\nThis is consistent with the project's testing strategy and the fact that every prior iteration added eval cases to validate changes.\n\n---\n\n### The `Mc`/`Mac` exemption is structurally fragile\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:342`\n\n**Impact**: The exemption `/^(Mc|Mac)[A-Z]/` applies to the whole word `w`, which is correct. However, the comment says \"Exempt Scottish/Irish names\" while the exemption actually covers any word beginning with `Mc` or `Mac` followed by a capital — including OCR noise that happens to start with those characters (unlikely but possible). More practically, similar legitimate name prefixes are not covered: \"O'Brien\" would not trigger the regex at all (apostrophe breaks the transition), but \"DeVito\" or \"LaRosa\" (Italian/French name particles) would fail the check and be flagged as garbled.\n\nThis is low frequency in recipe OCR, but if the exemption list is going to exist, it should either be minimal (what it is now) with a comment acknowledging the gap, or be broadened to cover the general category of name-particle capitalization. The current comment overstates completeness.\n\n**Suggestion**: Update the comment to be honest about scope:\n\n```typescript\n!/^(Mc|Mac)[A-Z]/.test(w) // Narrow exemption: Mc/Mac name prefixes only\n```\n\n---\n\n## Strengths\n\n- The placement inside the existing `if (words.length >= 2)` block is exactly right. It mirrors the structure and naming of `hasGarbledWord` immediately above it, making the code easy to follow.\n- The `w.length >= 3` guard is well-reasoned and documented in task-01.md.\n- The change is minimal and surgical — it does not refactor surrounding logic.\n\n---\n\n## Proactive Suggestions\n\n**Consolidate the two camelCase checks.** The single-word check at line 302 and the new multi-word check are now siblings that test the same pattern. If the `Mc`/`Mac` exemption is valid for multi-word, it is equally valid for single-word (a recipe book for \"McDonald's Classics\" contains a single-word title candidate \"McDonald's\"). Consider whether line 302 should also carry the exemption, and whether the two checks can be unified by removing the `words.length` guard and relying purely on the content test — though the current separate structure is easier to audit, so this is optional.\n\n**Eval case coverage.** The iteration 29 feedback shows the triggering case was `\"Xxyyzz salt and pepper\"` (Pattern 3). The task document lists verification cases but none appear to be wired into the test file. Adding even one integration test case reproducing the Pattern 3 input would prevent this regression from being re-introduced."}],"totalDurationMs":98432,"totalTokens":22969,"totalToolUseCount":14,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2838,"cache_read_input_tokens":18289,"output_tokens":1841,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2838},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}}}
